    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4564d991_413ba4f4",
        "filename": "gold-client/go/imgmatching/factory_test.go",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 185,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-23T19:40:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "suggestion: slices of test case structs can be somewhat annoying to debug (e.g. setting breakpoints). Because of this, I prefer to do\n\ntest :\u003d func(name string, ...) {\n   t.Run(name, func(t *testing.T) {...}\n}\n\ntest(\"all parameters missing, returns error\", missing, missing, \"required image matching parameter not found\")\ntest(\"...\")\n\nI also sort of like seeing the test function first, and then walking through the cases, when reading the test function.\n\nI\u0027ll reiterate on future CLs where this also could be applied. I\u0027m ok with slices of tests cases in some spots and test functions in others if one makes sense over another.",
      "revId": "9ad7db068725eaf218dde8ab89ff704278355f29",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3daee319_65f1977f",
        "filename": "gold-client/go/imgmatching/factory_test.go",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 185,
      "author": {
        "id": 10009
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-24T02:33:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I will stick with the slice of structs here because these tests do not always have the same number of parameters (want vs. error), and because of the complex values (e.g. want), both of which would result in hard to read, miltiline test(...) calls.\n\nGenerally I\u0027m OK with using the suggested approach as long as:\n1. The number of arguments is small.\n2. The arguments are small and simple (e.g. ints, short strings, short []int slices, very simple structs, etc.).\n3. All test cases require the same number of arguments.\n\nRationale:\n1. If the argument list grows too big it becomes harder to tell which argument is what, in which case a slice of structs with named fields is preferable.\n2. Argument values that require a lot of characters can make the argument list hard to read, result in long lines of code, cause the test(...) function call to span over several lines, etc.\n3. Things get muddy if some test cases require a different number of arguments: some of the arguments in the test(...) call would be set to their zero values, which can be hard to read; or alternatively, multiple versions of the test(...) function would be required. With a slice of structs, we would simply leave the corresponding field empty and it would take the zero-value by default.",
      "parentUuid": "4564d991_413ba4f4",
      "revId": "9ad7db068725eaf218dde8ab89ff704278355f29",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
